body:
i tried to "work around" this "feature" with the following small test script `dots.pdf` that i placed in my develoment webroot:
```php
<?php
// we'll return plain text
header('content-type: text/plain');

//header('content-disposition: attachment; filename="....txt"');
// chromium renames file to txt.txt
// ff renames file to txt

//header('content-disposition: attachment; filename*=utf-8\'\'....txt;');
// chromium renames file to txt.txt
// ff renames file to txt

// calling this script and appending '/....txt' in the url (st like http://localhost/owncloud/dots.php/....txt) as recommended in
// http://stackoverflow.com/questions/93551/how-to-encode-the-filename-parameter-of-content-disposition-header-in-http#216777
header('content-disposition: attachment;');
// chromium renames file to txt.txt
// ff renames file to txt

echo 'bla';
```

it seems we cannot work around the browser renaming dots. maybe that's a security feature?

also see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/7967079/special-characters-in-content-disposition-filename

i'll close this as won't fix.
